  { Units

    { Absolute lengths

      Most absolute length units are useful for printing.
      -
      The only exception is `px`.
      -
      But even so, absolute lenght units can be expressed in terms of `px` and vice versa.

      table { ll
        `px` ‚ėį Pixel
        `cm` ‚ėį Centimeter. `1cm` = `37.8px`
        `mm` ‚ėį Millimeter
        `Q` ‚ėį Quarter millimeter
        `in` ‚ėį Inch. `1in` = `96px`
        `pc` ‚ėį Pica. a ‚Öô of an inch.
        `pt` ‚ėį Point. 1/72th of an inch
      table }
    
    }
    { Relative lengths

      table { ll
       `vw` ‚ėį 1% of the viewport's width. The size of this unit is established with the value of `width` in `<‚Üí development/web/HTML/tags/meta/viewport[meta name="viewport"] content="width=xxx"‚Ä¶>`.
       `vh` ‚ėį 1% of the viewport's height.
       `vmin` ‚ėį 1% of the viewport's smaller dimension.
       `vmax` ‚ėį 1% of the viewport's larger dimension.
       `vb` ‚ėį 1% of the size of the initial containing block in the direction of the root element's block axis.
       `vi` ‚ėį 1% of the size of the initial containing block in the direction of the root element's inline axis.
       `svw`, `svh` ‚ėį 1% of the small viewport's width and height, respectively.
       `lvw`, `lvh` ‚ėį 1% of the large viewport's width and height, respectively.
       `dvw`, `dvh` ‚ėį 1% of the dynamic viewport's width and height, respectively.
      table }

